        <?php echo $this->stencil->setHeadline('VESA'); ?>
        <p><strong>VESA</strong> or the <strong>Video Electronics Standards Association</strong>, is an international non-profit corporation standards body for computer graphics formed in 1988 by <strong>NEC Home Electronics</strong>, maker of the MultiSync monitor line, and eight video display adapter manufacturers: <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('ATI Technologies', 'C'); ?>, Genoa Systems, Orchid Technology, Renaissance GRX, STB Systems, Tecmar, Video 7 and Western Digital/Paradise Systems.</p>
        <p>VESA's initial goal was to produce a standard for 800x600 <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('SVGA', 'ITH'); ?> resolution video displays. Since then VESA has issued a number of standards, mostly relating to the function of video peripherals in personal computers.</p>
        <p>In November 2010, VESA announced a cooperative agreement with the <strong>Wireless Gigabit Alliance (WiGig)</strong> for sharing technology expertise and specifications to develop multi-gigabit wireless DisplayPort capabilities. DisplayPort is a VESA technology that provides digital display connectivity for Monitor mount.</p>
